subject: Aarch64: Replace macro __x86_64__ with generic macro __LP64__
commitMessage:
Aarch64: Replace macro __x86_64__ with generic macro __LP64__

Package wrt-plugins-common cannot be built for the architecture
aarch64 because of the following error:

error: 'std::string WrtDeviceApis::CommonsJavaScript::Converter::toString(std::size_t)' cannot be overloaded

For architecture x86_64 this error also occurs, but the build of
erroneous function is disabled by the use of macro __x86_64__, which
is defined when the build is performed for x86_64 architecture.

We decided to disable the build of this function for aarch64, too.
It is done by replacement of macro __x86_64__ with more generic macro
__LP64__, which is defined both for x86_64 and aarch64 or any other
64-bit architecture.

The build for other architectures has been verified in the following
OBS project:

https://build.tizen.org/project/show?project=devel%3Aarm_toolchain%3AMobile%3Atest

Change-Id: I73ddd310431d77ad3df2da60a37bc454f36d2e7f
Signed-off-by: Ilya Palachev <i.palachev@samsung.com>

comments.message: Patch Set 1: Verified; Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Patch Set 1:

This package (the original package, not blaming this specific patch) is a classic example of horrific misuse of rpm post scripts.  We should take this as an opportunity to actually fix the package instead of attempting to follow the existing logic and stick another wad of bubblegum into the hopeless structure.

But... I'm a bit confused on what its actually trying to do.  Why are we nuking these files in the post section instead of just managing the file using the normal rpm mechanism?

Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this

yes exactly, lets try and minimize content of %post completely instead of being misled by existing logic

Patch Set 1:

This patch will just work as a security in case of update, avoiding to suppress wrt-plugins-common.conf conf file.
Basically, during an update, the postun of the old package is done after the post of the new one (see http://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Packaging:ScriptletSnippets).
Anyway, I agree with your point of view, real fix should be done! ;-)
